    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="798"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d798">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War/10–644</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé to the Czechoslovak Government in Exile</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-06">October 6,
                            1944</date>.<lb/>[Received October 14.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In continuation of my telegram No. 17 and
                    despatch No. 189 of October 2, 1944<note n="39" xml:id="d798fn39">Neither
                        printed.</note> reporting the willingness of the Czechoslovak Government to
                    associate itself with a possible declaration by the United Nations warning
                    Germany against a reported plan to exterminate the inmates of certain prison
                    camps, I have the honor to transmit a copy of a note of October 4, 1944<note
                        n="40" xml:id="d798fn40">Not printed.</note> from Mr. Jan Masaryk,
                    Czechoslovak Minister of Foreign Affairs, in which he quotes a telegram which he
                    has received on this subject from the World Jewish Congress in New York. On
                    behalf of his Government, Mr. Masaryk also asks the United States Government to
                    consider whether there is any possibility of assisting the internees whose lives
                    are evidently in extreme danger, and adds that he is also approaching the
                    Governments of Great Britain and the Soviet Union on this subject.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Rudolf</hi> E. <hi rend="smallcaps">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
